# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cryptography-pyca
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] You should **ONLY** use it if you’re 100% absolutely sure that you know what you’re doing because this module is full of land mines, dragons, and dinosaurs with laser guns.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] RSA is a public-key algorithm for encrypting and signing messages.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] Unlike symmetric cryptography, where the key is typically just a random series of bytes, RSA keys have a complex internal structure with specific mathematical properties.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] Changed in version 3.0: Tightened restrictions on `public_exponent`.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] `key_size` describes how many bits long the key should be.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] Larger keys provide more security; currently `1024` and below are considered breakable while `2048` or `4096` are reasonable default key sizes for new keys.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] The `public_exponent` indicates what one mathematical property of the key generation will be.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] Unless you have a specific reason to do otherwise, you should always use 65537.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] Serialized keys may optionally be encrypted on disk using a password.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] In this example we loaded an unencrypted key, and therefore we did not provide a password.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] If the key is encrypted we can pass a `bytes` object as the `password` argument.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] There is also support for `loading public keys in the SSH format`.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] If you have a private key that you’ve loaded you can use `private_bytes()` to serialize the key.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] It is also possible to serialize without encryption using `NoEncryption`.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] For public keys you can use `public_bytes()` to serialize the key.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] A private key can be used to sign a message.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] This allows anyone with the public key to verify that the message was created by someone who possesses the corresponding private key.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] RSA signatures require a specific hash function, and padding to be used.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] Valid paddings for signatures are `PSS` and `PKCS1v15`.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] `PSS` is the recommended choice for any new protocols or applications, `PKCS1v15` should only be used to support legacy protocols.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] If your data is too large to be passed in a single call, you can hash it separately and pass that value using `Prehashed`.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] The previous section describes what to do if you have a private key and want to sign something.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] If you have a public key, a message, a signature, and the signing algorithm that was used you can check that the private key associated with a given public key was used to sign that specific message.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] You can obtain a public key to use in verification using `load_pem_public_key()`, `load_der_public_key()`, `public_key()` , or `public_key()`.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] If the signature does not match, `verify()` will raise an `InvalidSignature` exception.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] RSA encryption is interesting because encryption is performed using the **public** key, meaning anyone can encrypt data.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] The data is then decrypted using the **private** key.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] Like signatures, RSA supports encryption with several different padding options.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] Valid paddings for encryption are `OAEP` and `PKCS1v15`.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] `OAEP` is the recommended choice for any new protocols or applications, `PKCS1v15` should only be used to support legacy protocols.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] Changed in version 0.4: Added `salt_length` parameter.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] PSS (Probabilistic Signature Scheme) is a signature scheme defined in **RFC 3447**.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] It is more complex than PKCS1 but possesses a security proof.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] This is the recommended padding algorithm for RSA signatures.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] Pass this attribute to `salt_length` to get the maximum salt length available.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] Pass this attribute to `salt_length` to set the salt length to the byte length of the digest passed when calling `sign`.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] Note that this is **not** the length of the digest passed to `MGF1`.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] Pass this attribute to `salt_length` to automatically determine the salt length when verifying.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] Raises `ValueError` if used when signing.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] The padding’s mask generation function (MGF).
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] OAEP (Optimal Asymmetric Encryption Padding) is a padding scheme defined in **RFC 3447**.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] It provides probabilistic encryption and is proven secure against several attack types.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] This is the recommended padding algorithm for RSA encryption.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] PKCS1 v1.5 (also known as simply PKCS1) is a simple padding scheme developed for use with RSA keys.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] This padding can be used for signing and encryption.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] It is not recommended that `PKCS1v15` be used for new applications, `OAEP` should be preferred for encryption and `PSS` should be preferred for signatures.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] When used with OpenSSL 3.2 or older, our implementation of PKCS1 v1.5 decryption is not constant time.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] See Known security limitations for details.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] Computes the length of the salt that `PSS` will use if `PSS.MAX_LENGTH` is used.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] Changed in version 0.6: Removed the deprecated `salt_length` parameter.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] MGF1 (Mask Generation Function 1) is used as the mask generation function in `PSS` and `OAEP` padding.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] These classes hold the constituent components of an RSA key.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] They are useful only when more traditional Key Serialization is unavailable.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] The collection of integers that make up an RSA public key.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] The collection of integers that make up an RSA private key.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] With the exception of the integers contained in the `RSAPublicNumbers` all attributes of this class must be kept secret.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] Revealing them will compromise the security of any cryptographic operations performed with a key loaded from them.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] The `RSAPublicNumbers` which makes up the RSA public key associated with this RSA private key.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] `p`, one of the two primes composing `n`.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] `q`, one of the two primes composing `n`.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] A Chinese remainder theorem coefficient used to speed up RSA operations.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] A keyword-only argument that defaults to `False`.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] If `True` RSA private keys will not be validated.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] This significantly speeds up loading the keys, but is unsafe unless you are certain the key is valid.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] User supplied keys should never be loaded with this parameter set to `True`.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] If you do load an invalid key this way and attempt to use it OpenSSL may hang, crash, or otherwise misbehave.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] If you are trying to load RSA private keys yourself you may find that not all parameters required by `RSAPrivateNumbers` are available.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] In particular the Chinese Remainder Theorem (CRT) values `dmp1`, `dmq1`, `iqmp` may be missing or present in a different form.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] For example, OpenPGP does not include the `iqmp`, `dmp1` or `dmq1` parameters.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] The following functions are provided for users who want to work with keys like this without having to do the math themselves.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] Computes the `iqmp` (also known as `qInv`) parameter from the RSA primes `p` and `q`.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] Computes the `dmp1` parameter from the RSA private exponent (`d`) and prime `p`.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] Computes the `dmq1` parameter from the RSA private exponent (`d`) and prime `q`.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] Computes the RSA private_exponent (`d`) given the public exponent (`e`) and the RSA primes `p` and `q`.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] This implementation uses the Carmichael totient function to return the smallest working value of `d`.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] Older RSA implementations, including the original RSA paper, often used the Euler totient function, which results in larger but equally functional private exponents.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] The private exponents resulting from the Carmichael totient function, as returned here, are slightly more computationally efficient to use, and some modern standards require them.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] Computes the prime factors `(p, q)` given the modulus, public exponent, and private exponent.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] When recovering prime factors this algorithm will always return `p` and `q` such that `p > q`.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] Note: before 1.5, this function always returned `p` and `q` such that `p < q`.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] It was changed because libraries commonly require `p > q`.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] Our implementation of PKCS1 v1.5 decryption is not constant time.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] Decrypt data that was encrypted with the public key.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] An RSA public key object corresponding to the values of the private key.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] Changed in version 1.6: `Prehashed` can now be used as an `algorithm`.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] Sign one block of data which can be verified later by others using the public key.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] Allows serialization of the key to bytes.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] Encoding ( `PEM` or `DER`), format ( `TraditionalOpenSSL`, `OpenSSH` or `PKCS8`) and encryption algorithm (such as `BestAvailableEncryption` or `NoEncryption`) are chosen to define the exact serialization.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] Encoding ( `PEM` or `DER`) and format ( `SubjectPublicKeyInfo` or `PKCS1`) are chosen to define the exact serialization.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] Verify one block of data was signed by the private key associated with this public key.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] Recovers the signed data from the signature.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] The data typically contains the digest of the original message string.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] The `padding` and `algorithm` parameters must match the ones used when the signature was created for the recovery to succeed.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] The `algorithm` parameter can also be set to `NoDigestInfo` to recover all the data present in the signature, without regard to its format or the hash algorithm used for its creation.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] For `PKCS1v15` padding, this method returns the data after removing the padding layer.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] For standard signatures the data contains the full `DigestInfo` structure.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] For non-standard signatures, any data can be returned, including zero-length data.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] Normally you should use the `verify()` function to validate the signature.
[src:cryptography-pyca/asymmetric-rsa] But for some non-standard signature formats you may need to explicitly recover and validate the signed data.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] In cryptography, a **block cipher** is a deterministic algorithm that operates on fixed-length groups of bits, called *blocks*.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] Block ciphers are the elementary building blocks of many cryptographic protocols.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] They are ubiquitous in the storage and exchange of data, where such data is secured and authenticated via encryption.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] A block cipher uses blocks as an unvarying transformation.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] Even a secure block cipher is suitable for the encryption of only a single block of data at a time, using a fixed key.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] A multitude of modes of operation have been designed to allow their repeated use in a secure way to achieve the other security goals of confidentiality and authenticity.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] However, block ciphers may also feature as building blocks in other cryptographic protocols, such as universal hash functions and pseudorandom number generators.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] A block cipher consists of two paired algorithms, one for encryption, *E*, and the other for decryption, *D*.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] Both algorithms accept two inputs: an input block of size *n* bits and a key of size *k* bits; and both yield an *n*-bit output block.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] The decryption algorithm *D* is defined to be the inverse function of encryption, i.e., *D* = *E*−1.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] which takes as input a key *K*, of bit length *k* (called the *key size*), and a bit string *P*, of length *n* (called the *block size*), and returns a string *C* of *n* bits.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] *P* is called the plaintext, and *C* is termed the ciphertext.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] For each *K*, the function *E**K*(*P*) is required to be an invertible mapping on {0,1}*n*.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] For example, a block cipher encryption algorithm might take a 128-bit block of plaintext as input, and output a corresponding 128-bit block of ciphertext.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] The exact transformation is controlled using a second input – the secret key.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] Decryption is similar: the decryption algorithm takes, in this example, a 128-bit block of ciphertext together with the secret key, and yields the original 128-bit block of plain text.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] For each key *K*, *EK* is a permutation (a bijective mapping) over the set of input blocks.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] Each key selects one permutation from the set of $(2^{n})!$ possible permutations.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] The modern design of block ciphers is based on the concept of an iterated product cipher.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] In his seminal 1949 publication, *Communication Theory of Secrecy Systems*, Claude Shannon analyzed product ciphers and suggested them as a means of effectively improving security by combining simple operations such as substitutions and permutations.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] Iterated product ciphers carry out encryption in multiple rounds, each of which uses a different subkey derived from the original key.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] One widespread implementation of such ciphers named a Feistel network after Horst Feistel is notably implemented in the DES cipher.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] Many other realizations of block ciphers, such as the AES, are classified as substitution–permutation networks.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] The root of all cryptographic block formats used within the Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard (PCI DSS) and American National Standards Institute (ANSI) standards lies with the Atalla Key Block (AKB), which was a key innovation of the Atalla Box, the first hardware security module (HSM).
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] Atalla, founder of Atalla Corporation (now Utimaco Atalla), and released in 1973.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] The AKB was a key block, which is required to securely interchange symmetric keys or PINs with other actors in the banking industry.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] This secure interchange is performed using the AKB format.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] The Atalla Box protected over 90% of all ATM networks in operation as of 1998, and Atalla products still secure the majority of the world's ATM transactions as of 2014.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] The publication of the DES cipher by the United States National Bureau of Standards (subsequently the U.S.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] National Institute of Standards and Technology, NIST) in 1977 was fundamental in the public understanding of modern block cipher design.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] It also influenced the academic development of cryptanalytic attacks.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] Both differential and linear cryptanalysis arose out of studies on DES design.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] As of 2016, there is a palette of attack techniques against which a block cipher must be secure, in addition to being robust against brute-force attacks.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] where $M_{0}$ is the plaintext and $M_{r}$ the ciphertext, with *r* being the number of rounds.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] Frequently, key whitening is used in addition to this.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] Given one of the standard iterated block cipher design schemes, it is fairly easy to construct a block cipher that is cryptographically secure, simply by using a large number of rounds.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] However, this will make the cipher inefficient.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] Thus, efficiency is the most important additional design criterion for professional ciphers.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] Further, a good block cipher is designed to avoid side-channel attacks, such as branch prediction and input-dependent memory accesses that might leak secret data via the cache state or the execution time.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] In addition, the cipher should be concise, for small hardware and software implementations.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] One important type of iterated block cipher known as a *substitution–permutation network (SPN)* takes a block of the plaintext and the key as inputs and applies several alternating rounds consisting of a substitution stage followed by a permutation stage—to produce each block of ciphertext output.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] The non-linear substitution stage mixes the key bits with those of the plaintext, creating Shannon's *confusion*.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] The linear permutation stage then dissipates redundancies, creating *diffusion*.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] A *substitution box (S-box)* substitutes a small block of input bits with another block of output bits.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] This substitution must be one-to-one, to ensure invertibility (hence decryption).
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] A secure S-box will have the property that changing one input bit will change about half of the output bits on average, exhibiting what is known as the avalanche effect—i.e. it has the property that each output bit will depend on every input bit.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] A *permutation box (P-box)* is a permutation of all the bits: it takes the outputs of all the S-boxes of one round, permutes the bits, and feeds them into the S-boxes of the next round.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] A good P-box has the property that the output bits of any S-box are distributed to as many S-box inputs as possible.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] At each round, the round key (obtained from the key with some simple operations, for instance, using S-boxes and P-boxes) is combined using some group operation, typically XOR.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] Decryption is done by simply reversing the process (using the inverses of the S-boxes and P-boxes and applying the round keys in reversed order).
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] In a *Feistel cipher*, the block of plain text to be encrypted is split into two equal-sized halves.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] The round function is applied to one half, using a subkey, and then the output is XORed with the other half.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] Let ${\rm {F}}$ be the round function and let $K_{0},K_{1},\ldots ,K_{n}$ be the sub-keys for the rounds $0,1,\ldots ,n$ respectively.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] One advantage of the Feistel model compared to a substitution–permutation network is that the round function ${\rm {F}}$ does not have to be invertible.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] The Lai–Massey scheme offers security properties similar to those of the Feistel structure.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] It also shares the advantage that the round function $\mathrm {F}$ does not have to be invertible.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] Another similarity is that it also splits the input block into two equal pieces.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] However, the round function is applied to the difference between the two, and the result is then added to both half blocks.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] Let $\mathrm {F}$ be the round function and $\mathrm {H}$ a half-round function and let $K_{0},K_{1},\ldots ,K_{n}$ be the sub-keys for the rounds $0,1,\ldots ,n$ respectively.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] Many modern block ciphers and hashes are **ARX** algorithms—their round function involves only three operations: (A) modular addition, (R) rotation with fixed rotation amounts, and (X) XOR.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] Examples include ChaCha20, Speck, XXTEA, and BLAKE.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] Many authors draw an ARX network, a kind of data flow diagram, to illustrate such a round function.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] These ARX operations are popular because they are relatively fast and cheap in hardware and software, their implementation can be made extremely simple, and also because they run in constant time, and therefore are immune to timing attacks.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] The rotational cryptanalysis technique attempts to attack such round functions.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] Other operations often used in block ciphers include data-dependent rotations as in RC5 and RC6, a substitution box implemented as a lookup table as in Data Encryption Standard and Advanced Encryption Standard, a permutation box, and multiplication as in IDEA.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] A block cipher by itself allows encryption only of a single data block of the cipher's block length.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] For a variable-length message, the data must first be partitioned into separate cipher blocks.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] In the simplest case, known as electronic codebook (ECB) mode, a message is first split into separate blocks of the cipher's block size (possibly extending the last block with padding bits), and then each block is encrypted and decrypted independently.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] However, such a naive method is generally insecure because equal plaintext blocks will always generate equal ciphertext blocks (for the same key), so patterns in the plaintext message become evident in the ciphertext output.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] To overcome this limitation, several so-called block cipher modes of operation have been designed and specified in national recommendations such as NIST 800-38A and BSI TR-02102 and international standards such as ISO/IEC 10116.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] The general concept is to use randomization of the plaintext data based on an additional input value, frequently called an initialization vector, to create what is termed probabilistic encryption.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] In the popular cipher block chaining (CBC) mode, for encryption to be secure the initialization vector passed along with the plaintext message must be a random or pseudo-random value, which is added in an exclusive-or manner to the first plaintext block before it is encrypted.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] The resultant ciphertext block is then used as the new initialization vector for the next plaintext block.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] In the cipher feedback (CFB) mode, which emulates a self-synchronizing stream cipher, the initialization vector is first encrypted and then added to the plaintext block.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] The output feedback (OFB) mode repeatedly encrypts the initialization vector to create a key stream for the emulation of a synchronous stream cipher.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] From a security-theoretic point of view, modes of operation must provide what is known as semantic security.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] Informally, it means that given some ciphertext under an unknown key one cannot practically derive any information from the ciphertext (other than the length of the message) over what one would have known without seeing the ciphertext.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] It has been shown that all of the modes discussed above, with the exception of the ECB mode, provide this property under so-called chosen plaintext attacks.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] Some modes such as the CBC mode only operate on complete plaintext blocks.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] Simply extending the last block of a message with zero bits is insufficient since it does not allow a receiver to easily distinguish messages that differ only in the number of padding bits.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] More importantly, such a simple solution gives rise to very efficient padding oracle attacks.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] A suitable padding scheme is therefore needed to extend the last plaintext block to the cipher's block size.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] Cryptanalysis is the technique in which ciphers are decrypted without knowledge of the used key.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] This property results in the cipher's security degrading quadratically, and needs to be taken into account when selecting a block size.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] There is a trade-off though as large block sizes can result in the algorithm becoming inefficient to operate.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] Earlier block ciphers such as the DES have typically selected a 64-bit block size, while newer designs such as the AES support block sizes of 128 bits or more, with some ciphers supporting a range of different block sizes.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] The discovery is attributed to Mitsuru Matsui, who first applied the technique to the FEAL cipher (Matsui and Yamagishi, 1992).
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] For a new block cipher design to have any credibility, it must demonstrate evidence of security against known attacks.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] When a block cipher is used in a given mode of operation, the resulting algorithm should ideally be about as secure as the block cipher itself.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] ECB (discussed above) emphatically lacks this property: regardless of how secure the underlying block cipher is, ECB mode can easily be attacked.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] On the other hand, CBC mode can be proven to be secure under the assumption that the underlying block cipher is likewise secure.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] Note, however, that making statements like this requires formal mathematical definitions for what it means for an encryption algorithm or a block cipher to "be secure".
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] This section describes two common notions for what properties a block cipher should have.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] Each corresponds to a mathematical model that can be used to prove properties of higher-level algorithms, such as CBC.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] This general approach to cryptography – proving higher-level algorithms (such as CBC) are secure under explicitly stated assumptions regarding their components (such as a block cipher) – is known as *provable security*.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] Informally, a block cipher is secure in the standard model if an attacker cannot tell the difference between the block cipher (equipped with a random key) and a random permutation.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] To be a bit more precise, let *E* be an *n*-bit block cipher.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] The attacker chooses an *n*-bit string *X*, and the person running the game tells him the value of *f*(*X*).
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] Step 2 is repeated a total of *q* times.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] The attacker guesses how the coin landed.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] The attacker, which we can model as an algorithm, is called an *adversary*.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] The function *f* (which the adversary was able to query) is called an *oracle*.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] Note that an adversary can trivially ensure a 50% chance of winning simply by guessing at random (or even by, for example, always guessing "heads").
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] Therefore, let *P**E*(*A*) denote the probability that adversary *A* wins this game against *E*, and define the *advantage* of *A* as 2(*P**E*(*A*) − 1/2).
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] It follows that if *A* guesses randomly, its advantage will be 0; on the other hand, if *A* always wins, then its advantage is 1.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] The block cipher *E* is a *pseudo-random permutation* (PRP) if no adversary has an advantage significantly greater than 0, given specified restrictions on *q* and the adversary's running time.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] If in Step 2 above adversaries have the option of learning *f*−1(*X*) instead of *f*(*X*) (but still have only small advantages) then *E* is a *strong* PRP (SPRP).
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] An adversary is *non-adaptive* if it chooses all *q* values for *X* before the game begins (that is, it does not use any information gleaned from previous queries to choose each *X* as it goes).
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] These definitions have proven useful for analyzing various modes of operation.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] For example, one can define a similar game for measuring the security of a block cipher-based encryption algorithm, and then try to show (through a reduction argument) that the probability of an adversary winning this new game is not much more than *P**E*(*A*) for some *A*.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] (The reduction typically provides limits on *q* and the running time of *A*.) Equivalently, if *P**E*(*A*) is small for all relevant *A*, then no attacker has a significant probability of winning the new game.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] This formalizes the idea that the higher-level algorithm inherits the block cipher's security.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] Block ciphers may be evaluated according to multiple criteria in practice.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] Lucifer is generally considered to be the first civilian block cipher, developed at IBM in the 1970s based on work done by Horst Feistel.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] A revised version of the algorithm was adopted as a U.S. government Federal Information Processing Standard: FIPS PUB 46 Data Encryption Standard (DES).
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] National Bureau of Standards (NBS) after a public invitation for submissions and some internal changes by NBS (and, potentially, the NSA).
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] DES was publicly released in 1976 and has been widely used.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] DES was designed to, among other things, resist a certain cryptanalytic attack known to the NSA and rediscovered by IBM, though unknown publicly until rediscovered again and published by Eli Biham and Adi Shamir in the late 1980s.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] The technique is called differential cryptanalysis and remains one of the few general attacks against block ciphers; linear cryptanalysis is another but may have been unknown even to the NSA, prior to its publication by Mitsuru Matsui.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] DES prompted a large amount of other work and publications in cryptography and cryptanalysis in the open community and it inspired many new cipher designs.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] DES has a block size of 64 bits and a key size of 56 bits.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] 64-bit blocks became common in block cipher designs after DES.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] Key length depended on several factors, including government regulation.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] Many observers in the 1970s commented that the 56-bit key length used for DES was too short.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] As time went on, its inadequacy became apparent, especially after a special-purpose machine designed to break DES was demonstrated in 1998 by the Electronic Frontier Foundation.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] An extension to DES, Triple DES, triple-encrypts each block with either two independent keys (112-bit key and 80-bit security) or three independent keys (168-bit key and 112-bit security).
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] As of 2011, the three-key version is still considered secure, though the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) standards no longer permit the use of the two-key version in new applications, due to its 80-bit security level.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] The *International Data Encryption Algorithm* (*IDEA*) is a block cipher designed by James Massey of ETH Zurich and Xuejia Lai; it was first described in 1991, as an intended replacement for DES.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] IDEA operates on 64-bit blocks using a 128-bit key and consists of a series of eight identical transformations (a *round*) and an output transformation (the *half-round*).
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] The processes for encryption and decryption are similar.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] IDEA derives much of its security by interleaving operations from different groups – modular addition and multiplication, and bitwise *exclusive or (XOR)* – which are algebraically "incompatible" in some sense.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] The designers analysed IDEA to measure its strength against differential cryptanalysis and concluded that it is immune under certain assumptions.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] No successful linear or algebraic weaknesses have been reported.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] As of 2012, the best attack which applies to all keys can break a full 8.5-round IDEA using a narrow-bicliques attack about four times faster than brute force.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] RC5 is a block cipher designed by Ronald Rivest in 1994 which, unlike many other ciphers, has a variable block size (32, 64, or 128 bits), key size (0 to 2040 bits), and a number of rounds (0 to 255).
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] The original suggested choice of parameters was a block size of 64 bits, a 128-bit key, and 12 rounds.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] A key feature of RC5 is the use of data-dependent rotations; one of the goals of RC5 was to prompt the study and evaluation of such operations as a cryptographic primitive.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] RC5 also consists of a number of modular additions and XORs.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] The general structure of the algorithm is a Feistel-like a network.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] The encryption and decryption routines can be specified in a few lines of code.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] The key schedule, however, is more complex, expanding the key using an essentially one-way function with the binary expansions of both e and the golden ratio as sources of "nothing up my sleeve numbers".
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] The tantalizing simplicity of the algorithm together with the novelty of the data-dependent rotations has made RC5 an attractive object of study for cryptanalysts.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] 12-round RC5 (with 64-bit blocks) is susceptible to a differential attack using 244 chosen plaintexts.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] 18–20 rounds are suggested as sufficient protection.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] The *Rijndael* cipher developed by Belgian cryptographers, Joan Daemen and Vincent Rijmen was one of the competing designs to replace DES.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] It won the 5-year public competition to become the AES (Advanced Encryption Standard).
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] Adopted by NIST in 2001, AES has a fixed block size of 128 bits and a key size of 128, 192, or 256 bits, whereas Rijndael can be specified with block and key sizes in any multiple of 32 bits, with a minimum of 128 bits.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] The block size has a maximum of 256 bits, but the key size has no theoretical maximum.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] AES operates on a 4×4 column-major order matrix of bytes, termed the *state* (versions of Rijndael with a larger block size have additional columns in the state).
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] It was designed as a general-purpose algorithm, intended as an alternative to the aging DES and free of the problems and constraints associated with other algorithms.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] At the time Blowfish was released, many other designs were proprietary, encumbered by patents, or were commercial/government secrets.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] Schneier has stated that "Blowfish is unpatented, and will remain so in all countries.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] The algorithm is hereby placed in the public domain, and can be freely used by anyone." The same applies to Twofish, a successor algorithm from Schneier.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] Wagner have described a generalized version of block ciphers called "tweakable" block ciphers.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] A tweakable block cipher accepts a second input called the *tweak* along with its usual plaintext or ciphertext input.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] The tweak, along with the key, selects the permutation computed by the cipher.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] If changing tweaks is sufficiently lightweight (compared with a usually fairly expensive key setup operation), then some interesting new operation modes become possible.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] The disk encryption theory article describes some of these modes.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] Block ciphers traditionally work over a binary alphabet.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] That is, both the input and the output are binary strings, consisting of *n* zeroes and ones.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] In some situations, however, one may wish to have a block cipher that works over some other alphabet; for example, encrypting 16-digit credit card numbers in such a way that the ciphertext is also a 16-digit number might facilitate adding an encryption layer to legacy software.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] This is an example of *format-preserving encryption*.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] More generally, format-preserving encryption requires a keyed permutation on some finite language.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] This makes format-preserving encryption schemes a natural generalization of (tweakable) block ciphers.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] In contrast, traditional encryption schemes, such as CBC, are not permutations because the same plaintext can encrypt multiple different ciphertexts, even when using a fixed key.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] Block ciphers can be used to build other cryptographic primitives, such as those below.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] For these other primitives to be cryptographically secure, care has to be taken to build them the right way.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] Just as block ciphers can be used to build hash functions, like SHA-1 and SHA-2 are based on block ciphers which are also used independently as SHACAL, hash functions can be used to build block ciphers.
[src:cryptography-pyca/block-cipher] Examples of such block ciphers are BEAR and LION.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Cryptography prior to the modern age was effectively synonymous with encryption, converting readable information (plaintext) to unintelligible nonsense text (ciphertext), which can only be read by reversing the process (decryption).
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] The sender of an encrypted (coded) message shares the decryption (decoding) technique only with the intended recipients to preclude access from adversaries.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] The cryptography literature often uses the names "Alice" (or "A") for the sender, "Bob" (or "B") for the intended recipient, and "Eve" (or "E") for the eavesdropping adversary.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Since the development of rotor cipher machines in World War I and the advent of computers in World War II, cryptography methods have become increasingly complex and their applications more varied.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Modern cryptography is heavily based on mathematical theory and computer science practice; cryptographic algorithms are designed around computational hardness assumptions, making such algorithms hard to break in actual practice by any adversary.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] While it is theoretically possible to break into a well-designed system, it is infeasible in actual practice to do so.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Such schemes, if well designed, are therefore termed "computationally secure".
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Theoretical advances (e.g., improvements in integer factorization algorithms) and faster computing technology require these designs to be continually reevaluated and, if necessary, adapted.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Information-theoretically secure schemes that provably cannot be broken even with unlimited computing power, such as the one-time pad, are much more difficult to use in practice than the best theoretically breakable but computationally secure schemes.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] The growth of cryptographic technology has raised a number of legal issues in the Information Age.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Cryptography's potential for use as a tool for espionage and sedition has led many governments to classify it as a weapon and to limit or even prohibit its use and export.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] In some jurisdictions where the use of cryptography is legal, laws permit investigators to compel the disclosure of encryption keys for documents relevant to an investigation.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Cryptography also plays a major role in digital rights management and copyright infringement disputes with regard to digital media.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] The first use of the term "cryptograph" (as opposed to "cryptogram") dates back to the 19th century – originating from "The Gold-Bug", a story by Edgar Allan Poe.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] The etymology of the term goes back to the Greek language; it is formed by two constituents: "crypton" (hidden), and "grapho" (to write).
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Until modern times, cryptography referred almost exclusively to "encryption", which is the process of converting ordinary information (called plaintext) into an unintelligible form (called ciphertext).
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Decryption is the reverse, in other words, moving from the unintelligible ciphertext back to plaintext.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] A cipher (or cypher) is a pair of algorithms that carry out the encryption and the reversing decryption.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] The detailed operation of a cipher is controlled both by the algorithm and, in each instance, by a "key".
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] The key is a secret (ideally known only to the communicants), usually a string of characters (ideally short so it can be remembered by the user), which is needed to decrypt the ciphertext.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] In formal mathematical terms, a "cryptosystem" is the ordered list of elements of finite possible plaintexts, finite possible cyphertexts, finite possible keys, and the encryption and decryption algorithms that correspond to each key.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Keys are important both formally and in actual practice, as ciphers without variable keys can be trivially broken with only the knowledge of the cipher used and are therefore useless (or even counter-productive) for most purposes.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Historically, ciphers were often used directly for encryption or decryption without additional procedures such as authentication or integrity checks.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] There are two main types of cryptosystems: symmetric and asymmetric.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] In symmetric systems, the only ones known until the 1970s, the same secret key encrypts and decrypts a message.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Data manipulation in symmetric systems is significantly faster than in asymmetric systems.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Asymmetric systems use a "public key" to encrypt a message and a related "private key" to decrypt it.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] The advantage of asymmetric systems is that the public key can be freely published, allowing parties to establish secure communication without having a shared secret key.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] In practice, asymmetric systems are used to first exchange a secret key, and then secure communication proceeds via a more efficient symmetric system using that key.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Examples of asymmetric systems include Diffie–Hellman key exchange, RSA (Rivest–Shamir–Adleman), ECC (Elliptic Curve Cryptography), and Post-quantum cryptography.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Secure symmetric algorithms include the commonly used AES (Advanced Encryption Standard) which replaced the older DES (Data Encryption Standard).
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Insecure symmetric algorithms include children's language tangling schemes such as Pig Latin or other cant, and all historical cryptographic schemes, however seriously intended, prior to the invention of the one-time pad early in the 20th century.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] In colloquial use, the term "code" is often used to mean any method of encryption or concealment of meaning.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] However, in cryptography, code has a more specific meaning: the replacement of a unit of plaintext (i.e., a meaningful word or phrase) with a code word (for example, "wallaby" replaces "attack at dawn").
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] A cypher, in contrast, is a scheme for changing or substituting an element below such a level (a letter, a syllable, or a pair of letters, etc.) to produce a cyphertext.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Cryptanalysis is the term used for the study of methods for obtaining the meaning of encrypted information without access to the key normally required to do so; i.e., it is the study of how to "crack" encryption algorithms or their implementations.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] English is more flexible than several other languages in which "cryptology" (done by cryptologists) is always used in the second sense above.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] RFC 2828 advises that steganography is sometimes included in cryptology.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] The study of characteristics of languages that have some application in cryptography or cryptology (e.g. frequency data, letter combinations, universal patterns, etc.) is called cryptolinguistics.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Cryptolingusitics is especially used in military intelligence applications for deciphering foreign communications.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Encryption attempted to ensure secrecy in communication, such as those of spies, military leaders, and diplomats.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] In recent decades, the field has expanded beyond confidentiality concerns to include techniques for message integrity checking, sender/receiver identity authentication, digital signatures, interactive proofs and secure computation, among others.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Simple versions of either have never offered much confidentiality from enterprising opponents.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] An early substitution cipher was the Caesar cipher, in which each letter in the plaintext was replaced by a letter three positions further down the alphabet.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Suetonius reports that Julius Caesar used it with a shift of three to communicate with his generals.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Atbash is an example of an early Hebrew cipher.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] The earliest known use of cryptography is some carved ciphertext on stone in Egypt (c.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] 1900 BCE), but this may have been done for the amusement of literate observers rather than as a way of concealing information.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] The Greeks of Classical times are said to have known of ciphers (e.g., the scytale transposition cipher claimed to have been used by the Spartan military).
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Steganography (i.e., hiding even the existence of a message so as to keep it confidential) was also first developed in ancient times.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] An early example, from Herodotus, was a message tattooed on a slave's shaved head and concealed under the regrown hair.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Other steganography methods involve 'hiding in plain sight,' such as using a music cipher to disguise an encrypted message within a regular piece of sheet music.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] More modern examples of steganography include the use of invisible ink, microdots, and digital watermarks to conceal information.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] In India, the 2000-year-old *Kama Sutra* of Vātsyāyana speaks of two different kinds of ciphers called Kautiliyam and Mulavediya.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] In the Kautiliyam, the cipher letter substitutions are based on phonetic relations, such as vowels becoming consonants.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] In the Mulavediya, the cipher alphabet consists of pairing letters and using the reciprocal ones.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] In Sassanid Persia, there were two secret scripts, according to the Muslim author Ibn al-Nadim: the *šāh-dabīrīya* (literally "King's script") which was used for official correspondence, and the *rāz-saharīya* which was used to communicate secret messages with other countries.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] David Kahn notes in *The Codebreakers* that modern cryptology originated among the Arabs, the first people to systematically document cryptanalytic methods.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Al-Khalil (717–786) wrote the *Book of Cryptographic Messages*, which contains the first use of permutations and combinations to list all possible Arabic words with and without vowels.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Ciphertexts produced by a classical cipher (and some modern ciphers) will reveal statistical information about the plaintext, and that information can often be used to break the cipher.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] After the discovery of frequency analysis, nearly all such ciphers could be broken by an informed attacker.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Such classical ciphers still enjoy popularity today, though mostly as puzzles (see cryptogram).
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] The Arab mathematician and polymath Al-Kindi wrote a book on cryptography entitled *Risalah fi Istikhraj al-Mu'amma* (*Manuscript for the Deciphering Cryptographic Messages*), which described the first known use of frequency analysis cryptanalysis techniques.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Language letter frequencies may offer little help for some extended historical encryption techniques such as homophonic cipher that tend to flatten the frequency distribution.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] For those ciphers, language letter group (or n-gram) frequencies may provide an attack.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Essentially all ciphers remained vulnerable to cryptanalysis using the frequency analysis technique until the development of the polyalphabetic cipher, most clearly by Leon Battista Alberti around the year 1467, though there is some indication that it was already known to Al-Kindi.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Alberti's innovation was to use different ciphers (i.e., substitution alphabets) for various parts of a message (perhaps for each successive plaintext letter at the limit).
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] He also invented what was probably the first automatic cipher device, a wheel that implemented a partial realization of his invention.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] In the Vigenère cipher, a polyalphabetic cipher, encryption uses a *key word*, which controls letter substitution depending on which letter of the key word is used.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] In the mid-19th century Charles Babbage showed that the Vigenère cipher was vulnerable to Kasiski examination, but this was first published about ten years later by Friedrich Kasiski.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Although frequency analysis can be a powerful and general technique against many ciphers, encryption has still often been effective in practice, as many a would-be cryptanalyst was unaware of the technique.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Breaking a message without using frequency analysis essentially required knowledge of the cipher used and perhaps of the key involved, thus making espionage, bribery, burglary, defection, etc., more attractive approaches to the cryptanalytically uninformed.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Security of the key used should alone be sufficient for a good cipher to maintain confidentiality under an attack.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Different physical devices and aids have been used to assist with ciphers.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] One of the earliest may have been the scytale of ancient Greece, a rod supposedly used by the Spartans as an aid for a transposition cipher.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] In medieval times, other aids were invented such as the cipher grille, which was also used for a kind of steganography.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] With the invention of polyalphabetic ciphers came more sophisticated aids such as Alberti's own cipher disk, Johannes Trithemius' tabula recta scheme, and Thomas Jefferson's wheel cypher (not publicly known, and reinvented independently by Bazeries around 1900).
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Many mechanical encryption/decryption devices were invented early in the 20th century, and several patented, among them rotor machines—famously including the Enigma machine used by the German government and military from the late 1920s and during World War II.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] The ciphers implemented by better quality examples of these machine designs brought about a substantial increase in cryptanalytic difficulty after WWI.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Cryptanalysis of the new mechanical ciphering devices proved to be both difficult and laborious.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] In the United Kingdom, cryptanalytic efforts at Bletchley Park during WWII spurred the development of more efficient means for carrying out repetitive tasks, such as military code breaking (decryption).
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] This culminated in the development of the Colossus, the world's first fully electronic, digital, programmable computer, which assisted in the decryption of ciphers generated by the German Army's Lorenz SZ40/42 machine.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Extensive open academic research into cryptography is relatively recent, beginning in the mid-1970s.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] In the early 1970s IBM personnel designed the Data Encryption Standard (DES) algorithm that became the first federal government cryptography standard in the United States.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] In 1976 Whitfield Diffie and Martin Hellman published the Diffie–Hellman key exchange algorithm.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] In 1977 the RSA algorithm was published in Martin Gardner's *Scientific American* column.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Since then, cryptography has become a widely used tool in communications, computer networks, and computer security generally.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Some modern cryptographic techniques can only keep their keys secret if certain mathematical problems are intractable, such as the integer factorization or the discrete logarithm problems, so there are deep connections with abstract mathematics.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] There are very few cryptosystems that are proven to be unconditionally secure.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] The one-time pad is one, and was proven to be so by Claude Shannon.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] There are a few important algorithms that have been proven secure under certain assumptions.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] For example, the infeasibility of factoring extremely large integers is the basis for believing that RSA is secure, and some other systems, but even so, proof of unbreakability is unavailable since the underlying mathematical problem remains open.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] In practice, these are widely used, and are believed unbreakable in practice by most competent observers.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] There are systems similar to RSA, such as one by Michael O.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Rabin that are provably secure provided factoring *n = pq* is impossible; it is quite unusable in practice.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] The discrete logarithm problem is the basis for believing some other cryptosystems are secure, and again, there are related, less practical systems that are provably secure relative to the solvability or insolvability discrete log problem.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] As well as being aware of cryptographic history, cryptographic algorithm and system designers must also sensibly consider probable future developments while working on their designs.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] For instance, continuous improvements in computer processing power have increased the scope of brute-force attacks, so when specifying key lengths, the required key lengths are similarly advancing.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] The potential impact of quantum computing are already being considered by some cryptographic system designers developing post-quantum cryptography.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] The announced imminence of small implementations of these machines may be making the need for preemptive caution rather more than merely speculative.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Claude Shannon's two papers, his 1948 paper on information theory, and especially his 1949 paper on cryptography, laid the foundations of modern cryptography and provided a mathematical basis for future cryptography.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] His 1949 paper has been noted as having provided a "solid theoretical basis for cryptography and for cryptanalysis", and as having turned cryptography from an "art to a science".
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] As a result of his contributions and work, he has been described as the "founding father of modern cryptography".
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Prior to the early 20th century, cryptography was mainly concerned with linguistic and lexicographic patterns.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Since then cryptography has broadened in scope, and now makes extensive use of mathematical subdisciplines, including information theory, computational complexity, statistics, combinatorics, abstract algebra, number theory, and finite mathematics.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Cryptography is also a branch of engineering, but an unusual one since it deals with active, intelligent, and malevolent opposition; other kinds of engineering (e.g., civil or chemical engineering) need deal only with neutral natural forces.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] There is also active research examining the relationship between cryptographic problems and quantum physics.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Just as the development of digital computers and electronics helped in cryptanalysis, it made possible much more complex ciphers.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Furthermore, computers allowed for the encryption of any kind of data representable in any binary format, unlike classical ciphers which only encrypted written language texts; this was new and significant.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Computer use has thus supplanted linguistic cryptography, both for cipher design and cryptanalysis.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Many computer ciphers can be characterized by their operation on binary bit sequences (sometimes in groups or blocks), unlike classical and mechanical schemes, which generally manipulate traditional characters (i.e., letters and digits) directly.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] However, computers have also assisted cryptanalysis, which has compensated to some extent for increased cipher complexity.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Research into **post-quantum cryptography** (PQC) has intensified because practical quantum computers would break widely deployed public-key systems such as RSA, Diffie–Hellman and ECC.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] A 2017 review in *Nature* surveys the leading PQC families—lattice-based, code-based, multivariate-quadratic and hash-based schemes—and stresses that standardisation and deployment should proceed well before large-scale quantum machines become available.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Symmetric-key cryptography refers to encryption methods in which both the sender and receiver share the same key (or, less commonly, in which their keys are different, but related in an easily computable way).
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] This was the only kind of encryption publicly known until June 1976.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Symmetric key ciphers are implemented as either block ciphers or stream ciphers.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] A block cipher enciphers input in blocks of plaintext as opposed to individual characters, the input form used by a stream cipher.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] The Data Encryption Standard (DES) and the Advanced Encryption Standard (AES) are block cipher designs that have been designated cryptography standards by the US government (though DES's designation was finally withdrawn after the AES was adopted).
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Despite its deprecation as an official standard, DES (especially its still-approved and much more secure triple-DES variant) remains quite popular; it is used across a wide range of applications, from ATM encryption to e-mail privacy and secure remote access.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Many other block ciphers have been designed and released, with considerable variation in quality.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Many, even some designed by capable practitioners, have been thoroughly broken, such as FEAL.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Stream ciphers, in contrast to the 'block' type, create an arbitrarily long stream of key material, which is combined with the plaintext bit-by-bit or character-by-character, somewhat like the one-time pad.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] In a stream cipher, the output stream is created based on a hidden internal state that changes as the cipher operates.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] That internal state is initially set up using the secret key material.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Block ciphers can be used as stream ciphers by generating blocks of a keystream (in place of a Pseudorandom number generator) and applying an XOR operation to each bit of the plaintext with each bit of the keystream.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Message authentication codes (MACs) are much like cryptographic hash functions, except that a secret key can be used to authenticate the hash value upon receipt; this additional complication blocks an attack scheme against bare digest algorithms, and so has been thought worth the effort.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Cryptographic hash functions are a third type of cryptographic algorithm.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] They take a message of any length as input, and output a short, fixed-length hash, which can be used in (for example) a digital signature.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] For good hash functions, an attacker cannot find two messages that produce the same hash.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] MD4 is a long-used hash function that is now broken; MD5, a strengthened variant of MD4, is also widely used but broken in practice.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] The competition ended on October 2, 2012, when the NIST announced that Keccak would be the new SHA-3 hash algorithm.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Unlike block and stream ciphers that are invertible, cryptographic hash functions produce a hashed output that cannot be used to retrieve the original input data.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Cryptographic hash functions are used to verify the authenticity of data retrieved from an untrusted source or to add a layer of security.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Symmetric-key cryptosystems use the same key for encryption and decryption of a message, although a message or group of messages can have a different key than others.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] A significant disadvantage of symmetric ciphers is the key management necessary to use them securely.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Each distinct pair of communicating parties must, ideally, share a different key, and perhaps for each ciphertext exchanged as well.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] The number of keys required increases as the square of the number of network members, which very quickly requires complex key management schemes to keep them all consistent and secret.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] In a groundbreaking 1976 paper, Whitfield Diffie and Martin Hellman proposed the notion of *public-key* (also, more generally, called *asymmetric key*) cryptography in which two different but mathematically related keys are used—a *public* key and a *private* key.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] A public key system is so constructed that calculation of one key (the 'private key') is computationally infeasible from the other (the 'public key'), even though they are necessarily related.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Instead, both keys are generated secretly, as an interrelated pair.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] The historian David Kahn described public-key cryptography as "the most revolutionary new concept in the field since polyalphabetic substitution emerged in the Renaissance".
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] In public-key cryptosystems, the public key may be freely distributed, while its paired private key must remain secret.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] The *public key* is used for encryption, while the *private* or *secret key* is used for decryption.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] While Diffie and Hellman could not find such a system, they showed that public-key cryptography was indeed possible by presenting the Diffie–Hellman key exchange protocol, a solution that is now widely used in secure communications to allow two parties to secretly agree on a shared encryption key.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] The X.509 standard defines the most commonly used format for public key certificates.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Diffie and Hellman's publication sparked widespread academic efforts in finding a practical public-key encryption system.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] This race was finally won in 1978 by Ronald Rivest, Adi Shamir, and Len Adleman, whose solution has since become known as the RSA algorithm.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] The Diffie–Hellman and RSA algorithms, in addition to being the first publicly known examples of high-quality public-key algorithms, have been among the most widely used.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Other asymmetric-key algorithms include the Cramer–Shoup cryptosystem, ElGamal encryption, and various elliptic curve techniques.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] A document published in 1997 by the Government Communications Headquarters (GCHQ), a British intelligence organization, revealed that cryptographers at GCHQ had anticipated several academic developments.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Ellis had conceived the principles of asymmetric key cryptography.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] In 1973, Clifford Cocks invented a solution that was very similar in design rationale to RSA.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Williamson is claimed to have developed the Diffie–Hellman key exchange.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Public-key cryptography is also used for implementing digital signature schemes.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] A digital signature is reminiscent of an ordinary signature; they both have the characteristic of being easy for a user to produce, but difficult for anyone else to forge.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Digital signatures can also be permanently tied to the content of the message being signed; they cannot then be 'moved' from one document to another, for any attempt will be detectable.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] In digital signature schemes, there are two algorithms: one for *signing*, in which a secret key is used to process the message (or a hash of the message, or both), and one for *verification*, in which the matching public key is used with the message to check the validity of the signature.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] RSA and DSA are two of the most popular digital signature schemes.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Digital signatures are central to the operation of public key infrastructures and many network security schemes (e.g., SSL/TLS, many VPNs, etc.).
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Public-key algorithms are most often based on the computational complexity of "hard" problems, often from number theory.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] For example, the hardness of RSA is related to the integer factorization problem, while Diffie–Hellman and DSA are related to the discrete logarithm problem.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] The security of elliptic curve cryptography is based on number theoretic problems involving elliptic curves.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Because of the difficulty of the underlying problems, most public-key algorithms involve operations such as modular multiplication and exponentiation, which are much more computationally expensive than the techniques used in most block ciphers, especially with typical key sizes.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] As a result, public-key cryptosystems are commonly hybrid cryptosystems, in which a fast high-quality symmetric-key encryption algorithm is used for the message itself, while the relevant symmetric key is sent with the message, but encrypted using a public-key algorithm.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Similarly, hybrid signature schemes are often used, in which a cryptographic hash function is computed, and only the resulting hash is digitally signed.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Cryptographic hash functions are functions that take a variable-length input and return a fixed-length output, which can be used in, for example, a digital signature.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] For a hash function to be secure, it must be difficult to compute two inputs that hash to the same value (collision resistance) and to compute an input that hashes to a given output (preimage resistance).
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] The goal of cryptanalysis is to find some weakness or insecurity in a cryptographic scheme, thus permitting its subversion or evasion.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] It is a common misconception that every encryption method can be broken.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] In connection with his WWII work at Bell Labs, Claude Shannon proved that the one-time pad cipher is unbreakable, provided the key material is truly random, never reused, kept secret from all possible attackers, and of equal or greater length than the message.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Most ciphers, apart from the one-time pad, can be broken with enough computational effort by brute force attack, but the amount of effort needed may be exponentially dependent on the key size, as compared to the effort needed to make use of the cipher.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] In such cases, effective security could be achieved if it is proven that the effort required (i.e., "work factor", in Shannon's terms) is beyond the ability of any adversary.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] This means it must be shown that no efficient method (as opposed to the time-consuming brute force method) can be found to break the cipher.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Since no such proof has been found to date, the one-time-pad remains the only theoretically unbreakable cipher.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Although well-implemented one-time-pad encryption cannot be broken, traffic analysis is still possible.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] There are a wide variety of cryptanalytic attacks, and they can be classified in any of several ways.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] A common distinction turns on what Eve (an attacker) knows and what capabilities are available.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] In a ciphertext-only attack, Eve has access only to the ciphertext (good modern cryptosystems are usually effectively immune to ciphertext-only attacks).
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] In a known-plaintext attack, Eve has access to a ciphertext and its corresponding plaintext (or to many such pairs).
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] In a chosen-plaintext attack, Eve may choose a plaintext and learn its corresponding ciphertext (perhaps many times); an example is gardening, used by the British during WWII.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] In a chosen-ciphertext attack, Eve may be able to *choose* ciphertexts and learn their corresponding plaintexts.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Finally in a man-in-the-middle attack Eve gets in between Alice (the sender) and Bob (the recipient), accesses and modifies the traffic and then forward it to the recipient.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Also important, often overwhelmingly so, are mistakes (generally in the design or use of one of the protocols involved).
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Cryptanalysis of symmetric-key ciphers typically involves looking for attacks against the block ciphers or stream ciphers that are more efficient than any attack that could be against a perfect cipher.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] For example, a simple brute force attack against DES requires one known plaintext and 255 decryptions, trying approximately half of the possible keys, to reach a point at which chances are better than even that the key sought will have been found.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] But this may not be enough assurance; a linear cryptanalysis attack against DES requires 243 known plaintexts (with their corresponding ciphertexts) and approximately 243 DES operations.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] This is a considerable improvement over brute force attacks.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Public-key algorithms are based on the computational difficulty of various problems.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] The most famous of these are the difficulty of integer factorization of semiprimes and the difficulty of calculating discrete logarithms, both of which are not yet proven to be solvable in polynomial time (**P**) using only a classical Turing-complete computer.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Much public-key cryptanalysis concerns designing algorithms in **P** that can solve these problems, or using other technologies, such as quantum computers.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] For instance, the best-known algorithms for solving the elliptic curve-based version of discrete logarithm are much more time-consuming than the best-known algorithms for factoring, at least for problems of more or less equivalent size.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Thus, to achieve an equivalent strength of encryption, techniques that depend upon the difficulty of factoring large composite numbers, such as the RSA cryptosystem, require larger keys than elliptic curve techniques.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] For this reason, public-key cryptosystems based on elliptic curves have become popular since their invention in the mid-1990s.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] While pure cryptanalysis uses weaknesses in the algorithms themselves, other attacks on cryptosystems are based on actual use of the algorithms in real devices, and are called *side-channel attacks*.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] If a cryptanalyst has access to, for example, the amount of time the device took to encrypt a number of plaintexts or report an error in a password or PIN character, they may be able to use a timing attack to break a cipher that is otherwise resistant to analysis.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] An attacker might also study the pattern and length of messages to derive valuable information; this is known as traffic analysis and can be quite useful to an alert adversary.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Poor administration of a cryptosystem, such as permitting too short keys, will make any system vulnerable, regardless of other virtues.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Social engineering and other attacks against humans (e.g., bribery, extortion, blackmail, espionage, rubber-hose cryptanalysis or torture) are usually employed due to being more cost-effective and feasible to perform in a reasonable amount of time compared to pure cryptanalysis by a high margin.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Much of the theoretical work in cryptography concerns cryptographic *primitives*—algorithms with basic cryptographic properties—and their relationship to other cryptographic problems.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] More complicated cryptographic tools are then built from these basic primitives.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] These primitives provide fundamental properties, which are used to develop more complex tools called *cryptosystems* or *cryptographic protocols*, which guarantee one or more high-level security properties.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Note, however, that the distinction between cryptographic *primitives* and cryptosystems, is quite arbitrary; for example, the RSA algorithm is sometimes considered a cryptosystem, and sometimes a primitive.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Typical examples of cryptographic primitives include pseudorandom functions, one-way functions, etc.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] One or more cryptographic primitives are often used to develop a more complex algorithm, called a cryptographic system, or *cryptosystem*.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Cryptosystems (e.g., El-Gamal encryption) are designed to provide particular functionality (e.g., public key encryption) while guaranteeing certain security properties (e.g., chosen-plaintext attack (CPA) security in the random oracle model).
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Cryptosystems use the properties of the underlying cryptographic primitives to support the system's security properties.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] As the distinction between primitives and cryptosystems is somewhat arbitrary, a sophisticated cryptosystem can be derived from a combination of several more primitive cryptosystems.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] In many cases, the cryptosystem's structure involves back and forth communication among two or more parties in space (e.g., between the sender of a secure message and its receiver) or across time (e.g., cryptographically protected backup data).
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Such cryptosystems are sometimes called *cryptographic protocols*.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Some widely known cryptosystems include RSA, Schnorr signature, ElGamal encryption, and Pretty Good Privacy (PGP).
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] More complex cryptosystems include electronic cash systems, signcryption systems, etc.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Some more 'theoretical' cryptosystems include interactive proof systems, (like zero-knowledge proofs) and systems for secret sharing.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Lightweight cryptography (LWC) concerns cryptographic algorithms developed for a strictly constrained environment.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] The growth of Internet of Things (IoT) has spiked research into the development of lightweight algorithms that are better suited for the environment.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] An IoT environment requires strict constraints on power consumption, processing power, and security.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Algorithms such as Ascon and SPECK are examples of the many LWC algorithms that have been developed to match the criteria for the CAESAR Competition and the standard set by the National Institute of Standards and Technology.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Cryptography is widely used on the internet to help protect user-data and prevent eavesdropping.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] To ensure secrecy during transmission, many systems use private key cryptography to protect transmitted information.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] With public-key systems, one can maintain secrecy without a master key or a large number of keys.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] But, some algorithms like BitLocker and VeraCrypt are generally not private-public key cryptography.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] For example, Veracrypt uses a password hash to generate the single private key.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] However, it can be configured to run in public-private key systems.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] The C++ opensource encryption library OpenSSL provides free and opensource encryption software and tools.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] The most commonly used encryption cipher suit is AES, as it has hardware acceleration for all x86 based processors that has AES-NI.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] A close contender is ChaCha20-Poly1305, which is a stream cipher, however it is commonly used for mobile devices as they are ARM based which does not feature AES-NI instruction set extension.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Cryptography can be used to secure communications by encrypting them.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] "End-to-end" encryption, where only sender and receiver can read messages, is implemented for email in Pretty Good Privacy and for secure messaging in general in WhatsApp, Signal and Telegram.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Operating systems use encryption to keep passwords secret, conceal parts of the system, and ensure that software updates are truly from the system maker.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Instead of storing plaintext passwords, computer systems store hashes thereof; then, when a user logs in, the system passes the given password through a cryptographic hash function and compares it to the hashed value on file.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] In this manner, neither the system nor an attacker has at any point access to the password in plaintext.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Encryption is sometimes used to encrypt one's entire drive.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] For example, University College London has implemented BitLocker (a program by Microsoft) to render drive data opaque without users logging in.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Cryptographic techniques enable cryptocurrency technologies, such as distributed ledger technologies (e.g., blockchains), which finance cryptoeconomics applications such as decentralized finance (DeFi).
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Key cryptographic techniques that enable cryptocurrencies and cryptoeconomics include, but are not limited to: cryptographic keys, cryptographic hash function, asymmetric (public key) encryption, Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA), End-to-End Encryption (E2EE), and Zero Knowledge Proofs (ZKP).
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] Estimates suggest that a quantum computer could reduce the effort required to break today’s strongest RSA or elliptic-curve keys from millennia to mere seconds, rendering current protocols (such as the versions of TLS that rely on those keys) insecure.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p01] To mitigate this "quantum threat", researchers are developing quantum-resistant algorithms whose security rests on problems believed to remain hard for both classical and quantum computers.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p02] Cryptography has long been of interest to intelligence gathering and law enforcement agencies.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p02] Secret communications may be criminal or even treasonous.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p02] Because of its facilitation of privacy, and the diminution of privacy attendant on its prohibition, cryptography is also of considerable interest to civil rights supporters.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p02] Accordingly, there has been a history of controversial legal issues surrounding cryptography, especially since the advent of inexpensive computers has made widespread access to high-quality cryptography possible.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p02] In some countries, even the domestic use of cryptography is, or has been, restricted.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p02] Until 1999, France significantly restricted the use of cryptography domestically, though it has since relaxed many of these rules.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p02] In China and Iran, a license is still required to use cryptography.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p02] Many countries have tight restrictions on the use of cryptography.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p02] Among the more restrictive are laws in Belarus, Kazakhstan, Mongolia, Pakistan, Singapore, Tunisia, and Vietnam.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p02] In the United States, cryptography is legal for domestic use, but there has been much conflict over legal issues related to cryptography.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p02] One particularly important issue has been the export of cryptography and cryptographic software and hardware.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p02] Probably because of the importance of cryptanalysis in World War II and an expectation that cryptography would continue to be important for national security, many Western governments have, at some point, strictly regulated export of cryptography.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p02] After World War II, it was illegal in the US to sell or distribute encryption technology overseas; in fact, encryption was designated as auxiliary military equipment and put on the United States Munitions List.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p02] Until the development of the personal computer, asymmetric key algorithms (i.e., public key techniques), and the Internet, this was not especially problematic.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p02] However, as the Internet grew and computers became more widely available, high-quality encryption techniques became well known around the globe.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p02] In the 1990s, there were several challenges to US export regulation of cryptography.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p02] Bernstein, then a graduate student at UC Berkeley, brought a lawsuit against the US government challenging some aspects of the restrictions based on free speech grounds.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p02] United States* ultimately resulted in a 1999 decision that printed source code for cryptographic algorithms and systems was protected as free speech by the United States Constitution.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p02] In 1996, thirty-nine countries signed the Wassenaar Arrangement, an arms control treaty that deals with the export of arms and "dual-use" technologies such as cryptography.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p02] The treaty stipulated that the use of cryptography with short key-lengths (56-bit for symmetric encryption, 512-bit for RSA) would no longer be export-controlled.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p02] Cryptography exports from the US became less strictly regulated as a consequence of a major relaxation in 2000; there are no longer very many restrictions on key sizes in US-exported mass-market software.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p02] The Mozilla Thunderbird and Microsoft Outlook E-mail client programs similarly can transmit and receive emails via TLS, and can send and receive email encrypted with S/MIME.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p02] Many Internet users do not realize that their basic application software contains such extensive cryptosystems.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p02] Another contentious issue connected to cryptography in the United States is the influence of the National Security Agency on cipher development and policy.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p02] The NSA was involved with the design of DES during its development at IBM and its consideration by the National Bureau of Standards as a possible Federal Standard for cryptography.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p02] DES was designed to be resistant to differential cryptanalysis, a powerful and general cryptanalytic technique known to the NSA and IBM, that became publicly known only when it was rediscovered in the late 1980s.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p02] According to Steven Levy, IBM discovered differential cryptanalysis, but kept the technique secret at the NSA's request.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p02] The technique became publicly known only when Biham and Shamir re-discovered and announced it some years later.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p02] The entire affair illustrates the difficulty of determining what resources and knowledge an attacker might actually have.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p02] Another instance of the NSA's involvement was the 1993 Clipper chip affair, an encryption microchip intended to be part of the Capstone cryptography-control initiative.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p02] Clipper was widely criticized by cryptographers for two reasons.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p02] The cipher algorithm (called Skipjack) was then classified (declassified in 1998, long after the Clipper initiative lapsed).
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p02] The classified cipher caused concerns that the NSA had deliberately made the cipher weak to assist its intelligence efforts.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p02] The whole initiative was also criticized based on its violation of Kerckhoffs's Principle, as the scheme included a special escrow key held by the government for use by law enforcement (i.e. wiretapping).
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p02] Cryptography is central to digital rights management (DRM), a group of techniques for technologically controlling use of copyrighted material, being widely implemented and deployed at the behest of some copyright holders.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p02] President Bill Clinton signed the Digital Millennium Copyright Act (DMCA), which criminalized all production, dissemination, and use of certain cryptanalytic techniques and technology (now known or later discovered); specifically, those that could be used to circumvent DRM technological schemes.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p02] This had a noticeable impact on the cryptography research community since an argument can be made that any cryptanalytic research violated the DMCA.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p02] Similar statutes have since been enacted in several countries and regions, including the implementation in the EU Copyright Directive.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p02] Similar restrictions are called for by treaties signed by World Intellectual Property Organization member-states.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p02] The United States Department of Justice and FBI have not enforced the DMCA as rigorously as had been feared by some, but the law, nonetheless, remains a controversial one.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p02] Niels Ferguson, a well-respected cryptography researcher, has publicly stated that he will not release some of his research into an Intel security design for fear of prosecution under the DMCA.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p02] Cryptologist Bruce Schneier has argued that the DMCA encourages vendor lock-in, while inhibiting actual measures toward cyber-security.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p02] Both Alan Cox (longtime Linux kernel developer) and Edward Felten (and some of his students at Princeton) have encountered problems related to the Act.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p02] Dmitry Sklyarov was arrested during a visit to the US from Russia, and jailed for five months pending trial for alleged violations of the DMCA arising from work he had done in Russia, where the work was legal.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p02] In 2007, the cryptographic keys responsible for Blu-ray and HD DVD content scrambling were discovered and released onto the Internet.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p02] In both cases, the Motion Picture Association of America sent out numerous DMCA takedown notices, and there was a massive Internet backlash triggered by the perceived impact of such notices on fair use and free speech.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p02] In the United Kingdom, the Regulation of Investigatory Powers Act gives UK police the powers to force suspects to decrypt files or hand over passwords that protect encryption keys.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p02] Failure to comply is an offense in its own right, punishable on conviction by a two-year jail sentence or up to five years in cases involving national security.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p02] Successful prosecutions have occurred under the Act; the first, in 2009, resulted in a term of 13 months' imprisonment.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p02] Similar forced disclosure laws in Australia, Finland, France, and India compel individual suspects under investigation to hand over encryption keys or passwords during a criminal investigation.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p02] In the United States, the federal criminal case of *United States v.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p02] Fricosu* addressed whether a search warrant can compel a person to reveal an encryption passphrase or password.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p02] The Electronic Frontier Foundation (EFF) argued that this is a violation of the protection from self-incrimination given by the Fifth Amendment.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p02] In 2012, the court ruled that under the All Writs Act, the defendant was required to produce an unencrypted hard drive for the court.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p02] In many jurisdictions, the legal status of forced disclosure remains unclear.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p02] The 2016 FBI–Apple encryption dispute concerns the ability of courts in the United States to compel manufacturers' assistance in unlocking cell phones whose contents are cryptographically protected.
[src:cryptography-pyca/cryptography-p02] As a potential counter-measure to forced disclosure some cryptographic software supports plausible deniability, where the encrypted data is indistinguishable from unused random data (for example such as that of a drive which has been securely wiped).
[src:cryptography-pyca/latest-fernet] Fernet guarantees that a message encrypted using it cannot be manipulated or read without the key.
[src:cryptography-pyca/latest-fernet] Fernet is an implementation of symmetric (also known as “secret key”) authenticated cryptography.
[src:cryptography-pyca/latest-fernet] Fernet also has support for implementing key rotation via `MultiFernet`.
[src:cryptography-pyca/latest-fernet] This class provides both encryption and decryption facilities.
[src:cryptography-pyca/latest-fernet] If you lose it you’ll no longer be able to decrypt messages; if anyone else gains access to it, they’ll be able to decrypt all of your messages, and they’ll also be able to forge arbitrary messages that will be authenticated and decrypted.
[src:cryptography-pyca/latest-fernet] The result of this encryption is known as a “Fernet token” and has strong privacy and authenticity guarantees.
[src:cryptography-pyca/latest-fernet] A secure message that cannot be read or altered without the key.
[src:cryptography-pyca/latest-fernet] This is referred to as a “Fernet token”.
[src:cryptography-pyca/latest-fernet] The encrypted message contains the current time when it was generated in *plaintext*, the time a message was created will therefore be visible to a possible attacker.
[src:cryptography-pyca/latest-fernet] Encrypts data passed using explicitly passed current time.
[src:cryptography-pyca/latest-fernet] See `encrypt()` for the documentation of the `data` parameter, the return type and the exceptions raised.
[src:cryptography-pyca/latest-fernet] The motivation behind this method is for the client code to be able to test token expiration.
[src:cryptography-pyca/latest-fernet] Since this method can be used in an insecure manner one should make sure the correct time (`int(time.time())`) is passed as `current_time` outside testing.
[src:cryptography-pyca/latest-fernet] Similarly to `encrypt()` the encrypted message contains the timestamp in *plaintext*, in this case the timestamp is the value of the `current_time` parameter.
[src:cryptography-pyca/latest-fernet] If successfully decrypted you will receive the original plaintext as the result, otherwise an exception will be raised.
[src:cryptography-pyca/latest-fernet] It is safe to use this data immediately as Fernet verifies that the data has not been tampered with prior to returning it.
[src:cryptography-pyca/latest-fernet] Decrypts a token using explicitly passed current time.
[src:cryptography-pyca/latest-fernet] See `decrypt()` for the documentation of the `token` and `ttl` parameters (`ttl` is required here), the return type and the exceptions raised.
[src:cryptography-pyca/latest-fernet] The caller can then decide if the token is about to expire and, for example, issue a new token.
[src:cryptography-pyca/latest-fernet] This class implements key rotation for Fernet.
[src:cryptography-pyca/latest-fernet] MultiFernet performs all encryption options using the *first* key in the `list` provided.
[src:cryptography-pyca/latest-fernet] MultiFernet attempts to decrypt tokens with each key in turn.
[src:cryptography-pyca/latest-fernet] A `cryptography.fernet.InvalidToken` exception is raised if the correct key is not found in the `list` provided.
[src:cryptography-pyca/latest-fernet] Key rotation makes it easy to replace old keys.
[src:cryptography-pyca/latest-fernet] You can add your new key at the front of the list to start encrypting new messages, and remove old keys as they are no longer needed.
[src:cryptography-pyca/latest-fernet] Token rotation as offered by `MultiFernet.rotate()` is a best practice and manner of cryptographic hygiene designed to limit damage in the event of an undetected event and to increase the difficulty of attacks.
[src:cryptography-pyca/latest-fernet] For example, if an employee who had access to your company’s fernet keys leaves, you’ll want to generate new fernet key, rotate all of the tokens currently deployed using that new key, and then retire the old fernet key(s) to which the employee had access.
[src:cryptography-pyca/latest-fernet] Rotates a token by re-encrypting it under the `MultiFernet` instance’s primary key.
[src:cryptography-pyca/latest-fernet] This preserves the timestamp that was originally saved with the token.
[src:cryptography-pyca/latest-fernet] If a token has successfully been rotated then the rotated token will be returned.
[src:cryptography-pyca/latest-fernet] If rotation fails this will raise an exception.
[src:cryptography-pyca/latest-fernet] See `Fernet.decrypt()` for more information.
[src:cryptography-pyca/latest-fernet] It is possible to use passwords with Fernet.
[src:cryptography-pyca/latest-fernet] To do this, you need to run the password through a key derivation function.
[src:cryptography-pyca/latest-fernet] `cryptography` provides several such functions; it is generally recommended to use `Argon2id`.
[src:cryptography-pyca/latest-fernet] In this scheme, the salt has to be stored in a retrievable location in order to derive the same key from the password in the future.
[src:cryptography-pyca/latest-fernet] The `Argon2id` parameters in the above code example are based on the recommendations of IRTF RFC 9106 for general applications.
[src:cryptography-pyca/latest-fernet] For memory-constrained applications, the RFC recommends `iterations=3` and `memory_cost=2**16`.
[src:cryptography-pyca/latest-fernet] Fernet is built on top of a number of standard cryptographic primitives.
[src:cryptography-pyca/latest-fernet] For complete details consult the specification.
[src:cryptography-pyca/latest-fernet] Fernet is ideal for encrypting data that easily fits in memory.
[src:cryptography-pyca/latest-fernet] As a design feature it does not expose unauthenticated bytes.
[src:cryptography-pyca/latest-fernet] This means that the complete message contents must be available in memory, making Fernet generally unsuitable for very large files at this time.
[src:cryptography-pyca/latest-x509] X.509 is a standard for public key infrastructure.
[src:cryptography-pyca/latest-x509] `cryptography` implements X.509 in accordance with **RFC 5280**, and is principally focused on WebPKI use cases.
[src:cryptography-pyca/latest-x509] X.509 certificates are commonly used in protocols like TLS.
[src:cryptography-pyca/latest-x509] In some cases we tolerate divergences from the these specifications, however these should be regarded as exceptional cases.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] Public key algorithms are fundamental security primitives in modern cryptosystems, including applications and protocols that offer assurance of the confidentiality and authenticity of electronic communications and data storage.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] They underpin numerous Internet standards, such as Transport Layer Security (TLS), SSH, S/MIME, and PGP.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] Compared to symmetric cryptography, public-key cryptography can be too slow for many purposes, so these protocols often combine symmetric cryptography with public-key cryptography in hybrid cryptosystems.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] Before the mid-1970s, all cipher systems used symmetric key algorithms, in which the same cryptographic key is used with the underlying algorithm by both the sender and the recipient, who must both keep the key secret.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] Of necessity, the key in every such system had to be exchanged between the communicating parties in some secure way prior to any use of the system – for instance, via a secure channel.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] This requirement is never trivial and very rapidly becomes unmanageable as the number of participants increases, when secure channels are not available, or when (as is sensible cryptographic practice) keys are frequently changed.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] In particular, if messages are meant to be secure from other users, a separate key is required for each possible pair of users.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] By contrast, in a public-key cryptosystem, the public keys can be disseminated widely and openly, and only the corresponding private keys need be kept secret.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] For example, a software publisher can create a signature key pair and include the public key in software installed on computers.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] Later, the publisher can distribute an update to the software signed using the private key, and any computer receiving an update can confirm it is genuine by verifying the signature using the public key.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] As long as the software publisher keeps the private key secret, even if a forger can distribute malicious updates to computers, they cannot convince the computers that any malicious updates are genuine.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] For example, a journalist can publish the public key of an encryption key pair on a website so that sources can send secret messages to the news organization in ciphertext.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] Only the journalist who knows the corresponding private key can decrypt the ciphertexts to obtain the sources' messages—an eavesdropper reading email on its way to the journalist cannot decrypt the ciphertexts.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] However, public-key encryption does not conceal metadata like what computer a source used to send a message, when they sent it, or how long it is.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] Public-key encryption on its own also does not tell the recipient anything about who sent a message—it just conceals the content of the message.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] Applications built on public-key cryptography include authenticating web servers with TLS, digital cash, password-authenticated key agreement, authenticating and concealing email content with OpenPGP or S/MIME, and time-stamping services and non-repudiation protocols.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] One important issue is confidence or proof that a particular public key is authentic, i.e., that it is correct and belongs to the person or entity claimed, and has not been tampered with or replaced by some (perhaps malicious) third party.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] A public key infrastructure (PKI), in which one or more third parties, known as certificate authorities, certify ownership of key pairs.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] This implies that the PKI system (software, hardware, and management) can be trusted by all involved.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] A web of trust decentralizes authentication by using individual endorsements of links between a user and their public key.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] PGP uses this approach, in addition to lookup in the domain name system (DNS).
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] The DKIM system for digitally signing emails also uses this approach.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] PGP, SSH, and the SSL/TLS family of schemes use this procedure; they are thus called hybrid cryptosystems.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] As with all security-related systems, there are various potential weaknesses in public-key cryptography.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] Aside from poor choice of an asymmetric key algorithm (there are few that are widely regarded as satisfactory) or too short a key length, the chief security risk is that the private key of a pair becomes known.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] All security of messages, authentication, etc., encrypted with this private key will then be lost.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] This is commonly mitigated (such as in recent TLS schemes) by using Forward secrecy capable schemes that generate an ephemeral set of keys during the communication which must also be known for the communication to be compromised.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] Additionally, with the advent of quantum computing, many asymmetric key algorithms are considered vulnerable to attacks, and new quantum-resistant schemes are being developed to overcome the problem.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] Beyond algorithmic or key-length weaknesses, some studies have noted risks when private key control is delegated to third parties.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] Research on Uruguay’s implementation of Public Key Infrastructure under Law 18.600 found that centralized key custody by Trust Service Providers (TSPs) may weaken the principle of private-key secrecy, increasing exposure to man-in-the-middle attacks and raising concerns about legal non-repudiation.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] All public key schemes are in theory susceptible to a "brute-force key search attack".
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] However, such an attack is impractical if the amount of computation needed to succeed – termed the "work factor" by Claude Shannon – is out of reach of all potential attackers.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] In many cases, the work factor can be increased by simply choosing a longer key.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] But other algorithms may inherently have much lower work factors, making resistance to a brute-force attack (e.g., from longer keys) irrelevant.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] Some special and specific algorithms have been developed to aid in attacking some public key encryption algorithms; both RSA and ElGamal encryption have known attacks that are much faster than the brute-force approach.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] None of these are sufficiently improved to be actually practical, however.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] Major weaknesses have been found for several formerly promising asymmetric key algorithms.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] The "knapsack packing" algorithm was found to be insecure after the development of a new attack.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] As with all cryptographic functions, public-key implementations may be vulnerable to side-channel attacks that exploit information leakage to simplify the search for a secret key.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] These are often independent of the algorithm being used.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] Research is underway to both discover, and to protect against, new attacks.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] Another potential security vulnerability in using asymmetric keys is the possibility of a "man-in-the-middle" attack, in which the communication of public keys is intercepted by a third party (the "man in the middle") and then modified to provide different public keys instead.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] Encrypted messages and responses must, in all instances, be intercepted, decrypted, and re-encrypted by the attacker using the correct public keys for the different communication segments so as to avoid suspicion.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] A communication is said to be insecure where data is transmitted in a manner that allows for interception (also called "sniffing").
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] These terms refer to reading the sender's private data in its entirety.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] A communication is particularly unsafe when interceptions can not be prevented or monitored by the sender.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] A man-in-the-middle attack can be difficult to implement due to the complexities of modern security protocols.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] However, the task becomes simpler when a sender is using insecure media such as public networks, the Internet, or wireless communication.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] In these cases an attacker can compromise the communications infrastructure rather than the data itself.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] A hypothetical malicious staff member at an Internet service provider (ISP) might find a man-in-the-middle attack relatively straightforward.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] Capturing the public key would only require searching for the key as it gets sent through the ISP's communications hardware; in properly implemented asymmetric key schemes, this is not a significant risk.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] In some advanced man-in-the-middle attacks, one side of the communication will see the original data while the other will receive a malicious variant.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] Asymmetric man-in-the-middle attacks can prevent users from realizing their connection is compromised.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] This remains so even when one user's data is known to be compromised because the data appears fine to the other user.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] This can lead to confusing disagreements between users such as "it must be on your end!" when neither user is at fault.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] Hence, man-in-the-middle attacks are only fully preventable when the communications infrastructure is physically controlled by one or both parties; such as via a wired route inside the sender's own building.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] In summation, public keys are easier to alter when the communications hardware used by a sender is controlled by an attacker.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] One approach to prevent such attacks involves the use of a public key infrastructure (PKI); a set of roles, policies, and procedures needed to create, manage, distribute, use, store and revoke digital certificates and manage public-key encryption.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] Web browsers, for instance, are supplied with a long list of "self-signed identity certificates" from PKI providers – these are used to check the *bona fides* of the certificate authority and then, in a second step, the certificates of potential communicators.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] An attacker who could subvert one of those certificate authorities into issuing a certificate for a bogus public key could then mount a "man-in-the-middle" attack as easily as if the certificate scheme were not used at all.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] An attacker who penetrates an authority's servers and obtains its store of certificates and keys (public and private) would be able to spoof, masquerade, decrypt, and forge transactions without limit, assuming that they were able to place themselves in the communication stream.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] Despite its theoretical and potential problems, Public key infrastructure is widely used.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] Examples include TLS and its predecessor SSL, which are commonly used to provide security for web browser transactions (for example, most websites utilize TLS for HTTPS).
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] Aside from the resistance to attack of a particular key pair, the security of the certification hierarchy must be considered when deploying public key systems.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] Some certificate authority – usually a purpose-built program running on a server computer – vouches for the identities assigned to specific private keys by producing a digital certificate.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] Public key digital certificates are typically valid for several years at a time, so the associated private keys must be held securely over that time.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] When a private key used for certificate creation higher in the PKI server hierarchy is compromised, or accidentally disclosed, then a "man-in-the-middle attack" is possible, making any subordinate certificate wholly insecure.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] Most of the available public-key encryption software does not conceal metadata in the message header, which might include the identities of the sender and recipient, the sending date, subject field, and the software they use etc.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] Rather, only the body of the message is concealed and can only be decrypted with the private key of the intended recipient.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] This means that a third party could construct quite a detailed model of participants in a communication network, along with the subjects being discussed, even if the message body itself is hidden.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] However, there has been a recent demonstration of messaging with encrypted headers, which obscures the identities of the sender and recipient, and significantly reduces the available metadata to a third party.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] The concept is based around an open repository containing separately encrypted metadata blocks and encrypted messages.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] Only the intended recipient is able to decrypt the metadata block, and having done so they can identify and download their messages and decrypt them.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] Such a messaging system is at present in an experimental phase and not yet deployed.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] Scaling this method would reveal to the third party only the inbox server being used by the recipient and the timestamp of sending and receiving.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] The server could be shared by thousands of users, making social network modelling much more challenging.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] During the early history of cryptography, two parties would rely upon a key that they would exchange by means of a secure, but non-cryptographic, method such as a face-to-face meeting, or a trusted courier.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] This key, which both parties must then keep absolutely secret, could then be used to exchange encrypted messages.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] A number of significant practical difficulties arise with this approach to distributing keys.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] Here he described the relationship of one-way functions to cryptography, and went on to discuss specifically the factorization problem used to create a trapdoor function.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] Ellis, a British cryptographer at the UK Government Communications Headquarters (GCHQ), conceived of the possibility of "non-secret encryption", (now called public key cryptography), but could see no way to implement it.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] In 1973, his colleague Clifford Cocks implemented what has become known as the RSA encryption algorithm, giving a practical method of "non-secret encryption", and in 1974 another GCHQ mathematician and cryptographer, Malcolm J.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] Williamson, developed what is now known as Diffie–Hellman key exchange.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] The scheme was also passed to the US's National Security Agency.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] Both organisations had a military focus and only limited computing power was available in any case; the potential of public key cryptography remained unrealised by either organization.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] These discoveries were not publicly acknowledged until the research was declassified by the British government in 1997.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] In 1976, an asymmetric key cryptosystem was published by Whitfield Diffie and Martin Hellman who, influenced by Ralph Merkle's work on public key distribution, disclosed a method of public key agreement.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] This method of key exchange, which uses exponentiation in a finite field, came to be known as Diffie–Hellman key exchange.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] This was the first published practical method for establishing a shared secret-key over an authenticated (but not confidential) communications channel without using a prior shared secret.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] Merkle's "public key-agreement technique" became known as Merkle's Puzzles, and was invented in 1974 and only published in 1978.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] This makes asymmetric encryption a rather new field in cryptography although cryptography itself dates back more than 2,000 years.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] In 1977, a generalization of Cocks's scheme was independently invented by Ron Rivest, Adi Shamir and Leonard Adleman, all then at MIT.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] The latter authors published their work in 1978 in Martin Gardner's Scientific American column, and the algorithm came to be known as RSA, from their initials.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] RSA uses exponentiation modulo a product of two very large primes, to encrypt and decrypt, performing both public key encryption and public key digital signatures.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] Its security is connected to the extreme difficulty of factoring large integers, a problem for which there is no known efficient general technique.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] A description of the algorithm was published in the Mathematical Games column in the August 1977 issue of Scientific American.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] Since the 1970s, a large number and variety of encryption, digital signature, key agreement, and other techniques have been developed, including the Rabin signature, ElGamal encryption, DSA and ECC.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] In addition to the algorithms developed within the open academic and standards communities, several countries have developed national public-key cryptography standards for use within their jurisdictions.
[src:cryptography-pyca/public-key-cryptography] These include SM2 and SM9 (China), GOST R 34.10-2012 (Russia), EC-KCDSA (South Korea), and DSTU 4145 (Ukraine).
[src:cryptography-pyca/symmetric-key-algorithm] Symmetric-key encryption can use either stream ciphers or block ciphers.
[src:cryptography-pyca/symmetric-key-algorithm] Stream ciphers encrypt the digits (typically bytes), or letters (in substitution ciphers) of a message one at a time.
[src:cryptography-pyca/symmetric-key-algorithm] Substitution ciphers are well-known ciphers, but can be easily decrypted using a frequency table.
[src:cryptography-pyca/symmetric-key-algorithm] Block ciphers take a number of bits and encrypt them in a single unit, padding the plaintext to achieve a multiple of the block size.
[src:cryptography-pyca/symmetric-key-algorithm] The Advanced Encryption Standard (AES) algorithm, approved by NIST in December 2001, uses 128-bit blocks.
[src:cryptography-pyca/symmetric-key-algorithm] Examples of popular symmetric-key algorithms include Twofish, Serpent, AES (Rijndael), Camellia, Salsa20, ChaCha20, Blowfish, CAST5, Kuznyechik, RC4, DES, 3DES, Skipjack, Safer, and IDEA.
[src:cryptography-pyca/symmetric-key-algorithm] Symmetric ciphers are commonly used to achieve other cryptographic primitives than just encryption.
[src:cryptography-pyca/symmetric-key-algorithm] Encrypting a message does not guarantee that it will remain unchanged while encrypted.
[src:cryptography-pyca/symmetric-key-algorithm] Hence, often a message authentication code is added to a ciphertext to ensure that changes to the ciphertext will be noted by the receiver.
[src:cryptography-pyca/symmetric-key-algorithm] Message authentication codes can be constructed from an AEAD cipher (e.g.
[src:cryptography-pyca/symmetric-key-algorithm] However, symmetric ciphers cannot be used for non-repudiation purposes except by involving additional parties.
[src:cryptography-pyca/symmetric-key-algorithm] Another application is to build hash functions from block ciphers.
[src:cryptography-pyca/symmetric-key-algorithm] See one-way compression function for descriptions of several such methods.
[src:cryptography-pyca/symmetric-key-algorithm] Many modern block ciphers are based on a construction proposed by Horst Feistel.
[src:cryptography-pyca/symmetric-key-algorithm] Feistel's construction makes it possible to build invertible functions from other functions that are themselves not invertible.
[src:cryptography-pyca/symmetric-key-algorithm] Symmetric ciphers have historically been susceptible to known-plaintext attacks, chosen-plaintext attacks, differential cryptanalysis and linear cryptanalysis.
[src:cryptography-pyca/symmetric-key-algorithm] Careful construction of the functions for each round can greatly reduce the chances of a successful attack.
[src:cryptography-pyca/symmetric-key-algorithm] It is also possible to increase the key length or the rounds in the encryption process to better protect against attack.
[src:cryptography-pyca/symmetric-key-algorithm] This, however, tends to increase the processing power and decrease the speed at which the process runs due to the amount of operations the system needs to do.
[src:cryptography-pyca/symmetric-key-algorithm] Most modern symmetric-key algorithms appear to be resistant to the threat of post-quantum cryptography.
[src:cryptography-pyca/symmetric-key-algorithm] Quantum computers would exponentially increase the speed at which these ciphers can be decoded; notably, Grover's algorithm would take the square-root of the time traditionally required for a brute-force attack, although these vulnerabilities can be compensated for by doubling key length.
[src:cryptography-pyca/symmetric-key-algorithm] For example, a 128 bit AES cipher would not be secure against such an attack as it would reduce the time required to test all possible iterations from over 10 quintillion years to about six months.
[src:cryptography-pyca/symmetric-key-algorithm] By contrast, it would still take a quantum computer the same amount of time to decode a 256 bit AES cipher as it would a conventional computer to decode a 128 bit AES cipher.
[src:cryptography-pyca/symmetric-key-algorithm] For this reason, AES-256 is believed to be "quantum resistant".
[src:cryptography-pyca/symmetric-key-algorithm] Symmetric-key algorithms require both the sender and the recipient of a message to have the same secret key.
[src:cryptography-pyca/symmetric-key-algorithm] All early cryptographic systems required either the sender or the recipient to somehow receive a copy of that secret key over a physically secure channel.
[src:cryptography-pyca/symmetric-key-algorithm] When used with asymmetric ciphers for key transfer, pseudorandom key generators are nearly always used to generate the symmetric cipher session keys.
[src:cryptography-pyca/symmetric-key-algorithm] However, lack of randomness in those generators or in their initialization vectors is disastrous and has led to cryptanalytic breaks in the past.
[src:cryptography-pyca/symmetric-key-algorithm] Therefore, it is essential that an implementation use a source of high entropy for its initialization.
[src:cryptography-pyca/symmetric-key-algorithm] A reciprocal cipher is a cipher where, just as one enters the plaintext into the cryptography system to get the ciphertext, one could enter the ciphertext into the same place in the system to get the plaintext.
[src:cryptography-pyca/symmetric-key-algorithm] A reciprocal cipher is also sometimes referred as **self-reciprocal cipher**.
[src:cryptography-pyca/symmetric-key-algorithm] Practically all mechanical cipher machines implement a reciprocal cipher, a mathematical involution on each typed-in letter.
[src:cryptography-pyca/symmetric-key-algorithm] Instead of designing two kinds of machines, one for encrypting and one for decrypting, all the machines can be identical and can be set up (keyed) the same way.
[src:cryptography-pyca/symmetric-key-algorithm] The majority of all modern ciphers can be classified as either a stream cipher, most of which use a reciprocal XOR cipher combiner, or a block cipher, most of which use a Feistel cipher or Lai–Massey scheme with a reciprocal transformation in each round.
